    "updated_at": "2015-06-27T17:21:46Z",
    "body": "If we recap this and evaluate the information we currently have, IsVisible detects whether the browser window is visible and chooses this option when the window is not visible (it also ultimately results in full screen on other OS expect Windows):\n\n``` c++\nwindow_->native_widget_private()->ShowWithWindowState(ui::SHOW_STATE_FULLSCREEN); \n```\n\nNow, this seems to work perfectly well on other operating systems expect Windows. But we found out here (https://codereview.chromium.org/1138383008) why it's not working with Windows. It is because the SHOW_STATE_FULLSCREEN state has not been supported in Windows. This is also validated since you tried commenting this line of code and it worked well on Windows.\n\nSo, now in order to eliminate this bug, we can simply comment the lines of code as you mentioned and get the required behavior. However, have you tested the code after commenting out the mentioned lines with other operating systems. It could be required with other OS and commenting those lines might break their functionality. So, I think a better solution would be check whether the OS is Windows and perform the task accordingly like here:\n\n``` c++\nvoid NativeWindowViews::SetFullScreen(bool fullscreen) {\n#if defined(OS_WIN)\n  // There is no native fullscreen state on Windows.\n  window_->SetFullscreen(fullscreen);\n  if (fullscreen)\n    NotifyWindowEnterFullScreen();\n  else\n    NotifyWindowLeaveFullScreen();\n#else\n  if (IsVisible())\n    window_->SetFullscreen(fullscreen);\n  else\n    window_->native_widget_private()->ShowWithWindowState(\n        ui::SHOW_STATE_FULLSCREEN);\n#endif\n}\n```\n\nMaybe someone else from core team can shed some more light. Is there anyone who could confirm this and what do you think? @frankhale \n"
  },
